# Unity Gameplay Iteration

- Implement requested gameplay changes directly in code; prefer small, shippable steps over long planning.
- Keep behavior configurable with serialized fields (`[SerializeField]`) instead of hardcoded constants.
- Group serialized fields with meaningful inspector headers (`[Header("...")]`) for readability (example: `Damage visual`).
- Centralize shared world/game-state values in manager classes; consumers should read from managers, not duplicate config.
- Preserve current behavior unless explicitly asked to change it; avoid unrelated refactors.
- Prefer simple, readable MonoBehaviour code (`Update`, clear helper methods) over heavy abstractions.
- When adding collisions/interactions, guard against double-processing in the same frame.
- Use smooth transitions for visuals/motion when requested (`Lerp`, `LerpAngle`, timers), with tunable speeds.
- Keep UI wiring practical: expose references in inspector and fail safely if optional refs are missing.

## Quick Patterns

```csharp
// ✅ Preferred: tunable gameplay values
[SerializeField] private float moveSpeed = 5f;
[SerializeField] private float cooldownSeconds = 1f;
```

```csharp
// ✅ Preferred: manager as single source of truth
float worldMinY = worldManager.WorldMinY;
float dirtTopY = worldManager.DirtTopY;
```
